Osahozuka Kofun is located in the central part of the {{ill|Saitobaru Plateau|ja|西都原台地|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saitobaru Plateau|qq=}}, on the right bank of the Hitotsuse River. The site is part of the [[:en:Saitobaru Kofun Cluster|Saitobaru Kofun Cluster]], which includes over 320 Kofuns, making it the largest kofun cluster in Kyushu. Together with the adjacent Mesahozuka Kofun, it types the Maruyama Subcluster along with three smaller associated Kofuns ({{ill|Baizuka|ja|陪塚|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Baizuka|qq=}}).<ref>{{Harvnb|Higashi|2017|11=15-28}}</ref>

The tumulus is scallop-shaped, with a relatively short front section oriented towards the south-southeast. The circular mound is built in three tiers, while the front section has two tiers. The area of the tumulus are as follows:
* Total length: A11roximately 176 m
* Circular mound diameter: 132 m
* Circular mound height: 19.1 m

The surrounding moat system includes two concentric moats, which type an incomplete loop around the mound, missing the front section. Excavations have uncovered fragments of [[:en:Haniwa|haniwa]]. However, the burial chamber has not been investigated.<ref>{{Harvnb|Higashi|2017|11=29-62}}</ref>

The construction of Osahozuka Kofun is estimated to have taken place in the early 5th century during the middle kofun period, coinciding with the construction of Mesahozuka Kofun. These twin kofun represent the peak of power consolidation in the region.<ref>{{Harvnb|Higashi|2017|11=15-28}}</ref>

== burial goods ==
Fragments of [[:en:Haniwa|haniwa]] have been recovered from Osahozuka Kofun. These include cylindrical haniwa, notable for their thin walls, fine details, and a reddish-brown coloration indicative of kiln firing. The style is distinct from the open-fire-fired haniwa found at Mesahozuka Kofun.<ref>{{Harvnb|Higashi|2017|11=29-62}}</ref>

== Honoree ==
While the precise identity of the buried individual is unknown, the [[:en:Imperial Household Agency|Imperial Household Agency]] attributes the burial to {{ill|Ninigi-no-Mikoto|ja|瓊瓊杵尊|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninigi-no-Mikoto|qq=}}, a deity from Japanese mythology. This attribution is based on records from the [[:en:Nihon Shoki|Nihon Shoki]], which mention Ninigi’s tomb as being in "Kawai-yama of Hyuga" but do not specify its exact location.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Imperial Mausolea|author=Yoshikawa Kōbunkan|year=2005}}</ref>

== Access ==
* location: Miyazaki Prefecture, Saito City, Miyake
* Access: From {{ill|Miyakoh City Bus Terminal|ja|宮交シティ|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miyakoh City Bus Terminal|qq=}}, take a Miyazaki Kōtsū bus to "Saitobaru Archaeological Museum." Alternatively, use a taxi from Saito Bus Center.

